ywhere, as to be at home.” Volume VI of this extraordinary series of selected papers is inescapably about endings, death, and silence. But death happens here to women still in the fight. An Awful Hush is about reformers trained “in the school of anti-slavery” trying to practice their craft in the age of Jim Crow and a new American Empire. It recounts new challenges to “an aristocracy of sex,” whether among the bishops of the Episcopal church, the voters of California, or the trustees of the University of Rochester. And it sends last messages about woman suffrage. As Stanton wrote to Theodore Roosevelt on the day before she died, “Surely there is no greater monopoly than that of all men, in denying to all women a voice in the laws they are compelled to obey.” With the publication of Volume VI, this series is now complete.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryxSources. 0aFeministsxArchivesxUnited States. 0aFeministszUnited StatesvArchives. 0aFeministszUnited StatesxArchives. 0aSuffragistsxArchivesxUnited States. 0aSuffragistszUnited StatesvArchives. 0aSuffragistszUnited StatesxArchives. 0aWomenxSuffragexHistoryxSourcesx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryxSources. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGordon, Ann D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311066333440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355345040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813553450.jpg  a978-3-11-066333-4  Rutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_